-------------------------------------------------------------------------
  BlueJ - implementation changes tracking database
-------------------------------------------------------------------------

People:

	mik	Michael Kolling (mik@insect.sd.monash.edu.au)
	bq	Bruce Quig (bruce@insect.sd.monash.edu.au)
	ajm	Andy Marks (amarks@insect.sd.monash.edu.au)


Format:

This file contains a list of bugs. "Bugs" is to be interpreted very widely
here: everything that is considered desirable to be changed is a bug,
including new features and improvements. Bugs are recorded as soon as they
are known. When a bug has made it into the database, it is never removed 
again. If it is not current anymore, it simply changes state (to "fixed"
or "dropped").


Each entry consists of the following fields:

@-------
@bug#  : a unique bug number
@short : a one line description
@prio  : priority (1..5) or ? Priorities are:
		1 crucial
		2 very important
		3 important
		4 less important
		5 long term
		? no priority assigned yet
@source: the person who reported the bug (preferably with email address)
@date  : the date entered (ISO format: yyyy-mm-dd)
@status: the current state of the bug; this is one of:
		Open
		In process (programmer-name)
		Closed, fixed (programmer-name, date) 
		Closed, dropped
	 Note: If a bug is "In process", the programmer's name is attached.
	       "Closed, dropped" marks a new feature that was dropped.
@fixrel: the release number in which this bug was fixed
@descr : a full descrition of the bug
@cause : the cause of the bug


The order in this file is roughly kept at:
  * open bugs 
	ordered by priority
  * closed bugs
	ordered by release-version and date


Entry template (copy this for new entry and increment the bug number 
in the template for the next one):

@-------
@bug#  : 00070
@short : 
@prio  : 
@source: 
@date  : 
@status: 
@fixrel: 
@descr : 
@cause : 

